05121nam a22006255i 9780822393627DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223936277 a10.1515/97808223936272doi  a(DE-B1597)554725  a(OCoLC)707825532  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN56.H57 7aSOC0120002bisacsh04a809.93353800aAfter Sex? :bOn Writing since Queer Theory /cJanet Halley, Andrew Parker, Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, Jonathan Goldberg, Michael Moon, Michèle Aina Barale. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (329 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. JANET HALLEY AND ANDREW PARKER -- tQueer Times -- tStill After -- tAfter Thoughts -- tGlad to Be Unhappy -- tDo You Smoke? Or, Is There Life? After Sex? -- tPost Sex -- tStarved -- tShame on You -- tEver After -- tWhat's Queer about Race? -- tQueer Theory Addiction -- tThe Sense of Watching Tony Sleep -- tOklahobo -- tPublic Feelings -- tQueers This -- tAfter Male Sex -- tLonely -- tWhen? Where? What? -- tQueer Theory -- tDisturbing Sexuality -- tAfter Sex?! -- tMelanie Klein and the Difference Affect Makes -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince queer theory originated in the early 1990s, its insights and modes of analysis have been taken up by scholars across the humanities and social sciences. In After Sex? prominent contributors to the development of queer studies offer personal reflections on the field's history, accomplishments, potential, and limitations. They consider the purpose of queer theory and the extent to which it is or is not defined by its engagement with sex and sexuality. For many of the contributors, a broad notion of sexuality is essential to queer thought. At the same time, some of them caution against creating an all-embracing idea of queerness, because it empties the term "queer" of meaning and assumes the universality of ideas developed in the North American academy. Some essays recall the political urgency of the late 1980s and early 1990s, when gay and lesbian activist and queer theory projects converged in response to the AIDS crisis. Other pieces exemplify more recent trends in queer critique, including the turn to affect and the debates surrounding the "antisocial thesis," which associates queerness with the repudiation of heteronormative forms of belonging. Contributors discuss queer theory's engagement with questions of transnationality and globalization, temporality and historical periodization. Meditating on the past and present of queer studies, After Sex? illuminates its future.Contributors. Lauren Berlant, Leo Bersani, Michael Cobb, Ann Cvetkovich, Lee Edelman, Richard Thompson Ford, Carla Freccero, Elizabeth Freeman, Jonathan Goldberg, Janet Halley, Neville Hoad, Joseph Litvak, Heather Love, Michael Lucey, Michael Moon, José Esteban Muñoz, Jeff Nunokawa, Andrew Parker, Elizabeth A. Povinelli, Richard Rambuss, Erica Rand, Bethany Schneider, Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick, Kate Thomas  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aQueer theory. 0aSexual orientation in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh1 aBarale, Michèle Aina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalley, Janet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoon, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aParker, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSedgwick, Eve Kosofsky